Background: Air pollutants cause endocrine disorders and hormone disruption.
The relationship between air pollutants and polycystic ovary syndrome (PCOS) must be carefully
investigated using a nationwide cohort. Methods: Data were extracted from two nationwide
databases, namely Longitudinal Health Insurance Database and Taiwan Air Quality Monitoring
Database, and analyzed. The study considered a range of data that began on 1 January 2000 and
ended on 31 December 2013. Women diagnosed with PCOS were excluded. Fromthe residential data,
